# Balatro Guide

Balatro is a roguelike deck-building game where you play poker hands to score points and defeat blinds (score targets). You collect Jokers that modify scoring rules, enhance cards with special abilities, and strategically build synergies to reach exponentially higher scores.

The game alternates between two main game phases:

1. **Playing Phase**: You start with an initial hand of 8 cards. You play a limited number of poker-like hands (hands left) which scores points according to the scoring system. Scores for the played hands sum together into the current score in order to reach the score target for the round. Under normal circumstances, you can play up to 5 cards at once. You have also access to a limited number of discards (discard left) where you can discard, under normal circumstances, up to 5 cards. In the case of a discard, you will draw from the deck the same amount of cards you have discarded and those cards are added to your current hand. If you successfully reach the target score, you will proceed to the Shop Phase otherwise it's Game Over.

2. **Shop Phase**: You can buy jokers, consumables, cards, and vouchers to modify the scoring system. The objective in this phase is to AGGRESSIVELY invest in powerful jokers and scaling mechanics.

## Initial Setup

When starting a new run, players begin with $4, a standard 52-card deck (13 ranks across 4 suits), 5 empty Joker slots, and 2 consumable slots. Each round provides 4 hands and 3 discards as the baseline to defeat blinds. Players draw 8 cards at the start of each round. The economic system rewards $1 per unspent hand after defeating a blind, plus $1 interest per $5 saved (maximum $5 interest at $25+).

## Blinds and Antes

Blinds are the main obstacle that the player must overcome during a run in Balatro. For each selected Blind, the player has to meet or surpass the required score to beat it, otherwise they will lose their run.

An Ante is made up of three Blinds in succession: a Small Blind, a Big Blind, and a random Boss Blind. Special Boss Blinds called Showdown Blinds only appear on the final level of a run, at Ante 8.

You start at Ante 1 and go up an Ante level for every Boss Blind defeated. By completing Ante 8 and finishing the Showdown Blind, the run is considered "won".

